""
"What you get is a dark, almost black, citrusy IPA that's given a bit more depth of character through dark malts. That's not to say that other black IPAs don't have the same roastiness and bittersweet chocolate characteristics, but they're a little bit fuller here. It seems to teeter, in fact, sometimes displaying more of the citrusy hops, and other times offering more of the toastiness, roastiness, nuttiness, deep caramel, and dark/bittersweet chocolate notes. Somehow the alcohol never really shows itself, although there are suggestions of it in the splash of dryness that hits you at the finish. But again, where this beer could have hit you with a long-lingering bitter and roasty finish, there's none of that... instead, it somehow manages to squeeze out a bit of sweetness that seems like a combination of very light creamy caramel and burnt (or nearly burnt) sugar. In that way Founders has done an excellent job in formulating an almost compellingly drinkable ""Imperial Black India Pale Ale"". Well worth trying."
""
