"O: great black ale along the lines of Dark Element, Dubhe, Wookey Jack, 'Self-Righteous, and Dark Horse's Special Reserve - nothing innovative, but everything exceptional. Must try, 'specially for fans of hoppy black ales."
"Poured a rich black body with brown highlights on the edge of the glass and a thin film of tan off-white head. Very nice looking and true to form for a dark ale. Scents of grapefruit, grapefruit peel, orange peel and flesh, and tropical fruit, light notes of pine resin, very light notes of chocolate and roast malt in the background. Overall impression of aroma is of a nice, hop-forward black ale with just enough depth from the malt coming through. Very nice and quite appealing. Flavor begins hoppy, with notes of grapefruit peel and pith, orange zest, light tropical fruit, moderate-light pine resin and hints of roasted malt. Middle opens up to be more bitter with strong notes of grapefruit and pomelo peel and pith, more abundant pine resin and medium levels of roast malt. Finish is dry with strong notes of grapefruit and pomelo peel and pith, pine resin, orange zest and medium-strong levels of roast malt with light alcohol in the background. Aftertaste is roast malt bitter pine resin and grapefruit peel and pith. Overall impression of flavor is of an excellent dark ale that is wonderfully hoppy, but still has a very good roast malt presence. Nice and drinkable. Mouthfeel is medium bodied with medium-light carbonation and a resinous feel upfront with a slick finish. Overall impression of mouthfeel is of a nice dark ale that is true to form, very similar to other hoppy beers. Easy drinking despite the body and quite pleasant. Overall this is a fantastic dark ale. Like many others it leans towards hops, but the overall profile is so well done that it compares quite well to Mountain Standard and Wookey Jack. Highly recommended."
